From: stopless-java-gc <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH 0063/N] metaspace.cpp: round word_size to even for 16-byte cap alignment

Phase 2 entry point. After 0060-0062 the JVM boots through GC init and
StubRoutines generation, then crashes in `ConstantPool::allocate` at
the `stp c1, c20, [c0]` instruction emitted by the inlined constructor.
The stp stores two 16-byte capabilities (vtable + first cap member) at
offset 0 of the freshly-allocated buffer. For this to work the buffer
must be 16-byte aligned.

Metaspace allocates in MetaWord units (= 8 bytes after the 0060
HeapWord/MetaWord refactor). If the previous allocation had an odd
word_size, the current one starts at an 8-byte-aligned but not
16-byte-aligned address, violating the alignment required by CHERI
capability stores.

Round word_size up to even in `Metaspace::allocate` under
`__CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__`. Costs at most 8 bytes per allocation;
guarantees subsequent allocations remain 16-byte aligned.

This fix advances JVM init past the ConstantPool stp crash, into the
next layer (capability tag violations on data loaded from
modules.jimage — Phase 2 work proper, see docs/02 §3).

Refs: docs/05_zgc_cheri_collision_report.md (patch 0063)

--- a/src/hotspot/share/memory/metaspace.cpp
+++ b/src/hotspot/share/memory/metaspace.cpp
@@ -895,6 +895,16 @@ size_t Metaspace::max_allocation_word_size() {
 // Callers are responsible for checking null.
 MetaWord* Metaspace::allocate(ClassLoaderData* loader_data, size_t word_size,
                               MetaspaceObj::Type type) {
+#ifdef __CHERI_PURE_CAPABILITY__
+  // CHERI purecap: MetaspaceObj subclasses (Klass, ConstantPool, Method, ...)
+  // contain capability-typed fields (vtable ptr, member pointers) that require
+  // 16-byte alignment. MetaWord is 8 bytes, so an odd word_size leaves the
+  // next allocation 8-byte-aligned, violating cap alignment. Round word_size
+  // up to even so every allocation lands on a 16-byte boundary.
+  if (word_size & 1) {
+    word_size++;
+  }
+#endif
   assert(word_size <= Metaspace::max_allocation_word_size(),
          "allocation size too large (" SIZE_FORMAT ")", word_size);

